body:
Solidity tests can be run by Remix unit testing plugin. It has a feature that sender and value of a tx can be customized. It's a cool feature and can be further improved to support more testing scenarios.

Remix unit testing plugin currently supports custom transaction context, where `msg.sender` and `msg.value` can be specified in the comments.
```Solidity
    /// Custom Transaction Context
    /// See more: https://remix-ide.readthedocs.io/en/latest/unittesting.html#customization
    /// #sender: account-1
    /// #value: 100
    function checkSenderAndValue() public payable {
        // account index varies 0-9, value is in wei
        Assert.equal(msg.sender, TestsAccounts.getAccount(1), "Invalid sender");
        Assert.equal(msg.value, 100, "Invalid value");
    }
```

However, the `msg.sender` and `msg.value` only apply for the test function. `msg.sender` of any external function call inside the test function is still the test contract itself. It is very inconvenient that I cannot specify `msg.sender` of a function call when writing tests. Testing scenarios are very limited because of this (the`msg.sender` of the external function call is always the test contract itself).

It would be great if the `msg.sender`/`msg.value` of any external function call can be override/specified as well, just like the testings written in js or other testing framework. The following is an example. The `msg.sender` of two calls to token `approve` function are override with different accounts

```Solidity
	/// #sender: account-0
	/// #value: 11000000000000000000
	function attack() payable public {
		/// #sender: account-1
		token.approve(address(attacker), 1e18); // account 1 approve attacker contract.
		/// #sender: account-2
		token.approve(address(victim), 10e18); // account 2 approve victim contract.

		// ---some testings ..----//

	}
```
